Watch this, I'm going to slip into the realm of radical anthro anarchy.
A fox is simply an animal that we perceive as a fox. An anthro fox would be one with human characteristics. A fox fursuit is not an anthro, as it's nothing more than a construction of non-fox materials designed to represent a fox. All of this also applies to a giraffe, helicopter, toaster, etc. Just replace "fox fursuit" with "toaster costume." A suit of armor, on the other hand, serves the explicit function of being worn, and with some exceptions, being worn by a human. On its own, sitting unoccupied in the corner, it lack any characteristics other than basic anatomical structure to be considered anthropomorphic. A human occupying it would give the armor sentience, sapience, emotion, motion, and mortality. The human wearing it simply becomes the organs necessary to allow all of these functions and characteristics. Yes, removing the human from the armor would cause it to stop being an anthro aside from physiology, but removing all of a human's internal organs would achieve the same thing. An occupied suit of armor is, by all means, an anthro.
